## Implications for Abortion Access and Public Health

### Practical Barriers to Access

- **Short Timeframe:** The six-week limit leaves a very narrow window for women to confirm pregnancy, make decisions, and obtain an abortion. Many women do not detect pregnancy until after six weeks, effectively banning abortion for most ([Medical News Today, 2021](https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/texas-abortion-law-implications-for-womens-health-and-safety)).

- **Mandatory Delays:** Existing Texas laws impose a 24-hour waiting period and mandatory sonograms, further reducing the time available to access abortion services ([Lilith Fund, 2021](https://www.lilithfund.org/what-senate-bill-8-means-for-texans/)).

- **Rural and Undocumented Populations:** Women in rural areas face long travel distances to clinics, and undocumented individuals may be unable to travel out of state due to immigration checkpoints, exacerbating access issues ([Lilith Fund, 2021](https://www.lilithfund.org/what-senate-bill-8-means-for-texans/)).

### Increased Out-of-State Travel

- **Surge in Out-of-State Abortions:** Since SB8 took effect, thousands of Texas residents have traveled to neighboring states such as Oklahoma, Kansas, and New Mexico to obtain abortions ([Washington Post, 2021](https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/09/01/texas-abortion-law-faq/)).

- **Financial and Logistical Burdens:** Travel involves costs for transportation, lodging, childcare, and time off work, disproportionately affecting low-income individuals ([Planned Parenthood Action, 2021](https://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/blog/texas-law-will-ban-abortion-at-6-weeks-and-let-anyone-sue-texans-who-help-someone-get-an-abortion)).

### Health Disparities and Maternal Outcomes

- **Disproportionate Impact on Black Women:** The law is projected to exacerbate existing health disparities, particularly among Black women who already face higher maternal mortality and morbidity rates in Texas ([Medical News Today, 2021](https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/texas-abortion-law-implications-for-womens-health-and-safety)).

- **Socioeconomic Effects:** Medicaid does not cover abortions, so low-income women reliant on Medicaid face increased barriers to care, potentially leading to worse health outcomes ([Chron, 2021](https://www.chron.com/politics/article/Texas-abortion-law-could-threaten-state-economy-16498858.php)).

